  "text": "The AQL query execution pipeline in ArangoDB follows this key flow:\n\n1. **AQL Parser (arangod/Aql/Parser.h)** - The `Parser` class handles the initial parsing of AQL query strings. Located in `arangod/Aql/Parser.cpp/.h`, it tokenizes and parses the input query using a lexer/scanner (referenced in the code comments as generated from Aql/tokens.ll) and builds an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) represented by `AstNode` objects. The Parser class has a `parse()` method that is the entry point.\n\n2. **Query Optimizer (arangod/Aql/Optimizer.h)** - The `Optimizer` class transforms the parsed AST into an optimized execution plan. Located in `arangod/Aql/Optimizer.cpp/.h`, it applies a series of transformation rules (defined in OptimizerRules.cpp) to the ExecutionPlan, creating multiple plans and selecting the best one based on cost estimation. The key method is `createPlans()`.\n\n3. **ExecutionEngine (arangod/Aql/ExecutionEngine.h)** - The `ExecutionEngine` class is the query execution runtime. Located in `arangod/Aql/ExecutionEngine.cpp/.h`, it manages the instantiation and execution of execution blocks. It coordinates the execution of the optimized plan and handles resource management through AqlItemBlockManager.\n\n4. **ExecutionBlock (arangod/Aql/ExecutionBlock.h)** - The `ExecutionBlock` base class defines the interface for individual execution operators in the plan. Located in `arangod/Aql/ExecutionBlock.cpp/.h`, each block processes data in a streaming fashion, implementing the `execute()` method that returns execution state, skip results, and data blocks. Various subclasses implement specific operations like scanning, filtering, aggregation, and joins.\n\n5. **RocksDBCollection (arangod/RocksDBEngine/RocksDBCollection.h)** - The `RocksDBCollection` class provides the storage engine interface for data retrieval from the RocksDB key-value store. Located in `arangod/RocksDBEngine/RocksDBCollection.cpp/.h`, it implements methods like `lookup()`, `insert()`, `update()`, `remove()`, and `getAllIterator()` that access underlying document data. It wraps the RocksDB engine and manages document access through transactions.\n\n6. **Transaction Manager (arangod/Transaction/Manager.h)** - The `Manager` class manages transaction lifecycle and state. Located in `arangod/Transaction/Manager.cpp/.h`, it tracks active transactions, handles transaction creation, coordination, commit, and abort operations. It maintains transaction state buckets and provides methods like `createManagedTrx()`, `commitManagedTrx()`, and `abortManagedTrx()`.\n\n7. **Transaction Methods (arangod/Transaction/Methods.h)** - The `Methods` class provides the transactional interface for queries to access collections and perform operations. Located in `arangod/Transaction/Methods.cpp/.h`, it coordinates between the execution blocks and the underlying collection implementations, ensuring ACID properties and handling transaction semantics.\n\nThe complete execution flow is: Query String → Parser (creates AST) → Optimizer (creates ExecutionPlan) → ExecutionEngine (instantiates ExecutionBlocks) → ExecutionBlock execution (calls RocksDBCollection methods under Transaction control) → Data Retrieval."
}

